{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_basil_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517170975/1938021701/0097.xml":{"full_text":"FINANCIAL NEWS\nThe Business Trend\nPrice Cuts In Steel\nMost observers apparently agree\nthat the price situation offers the\nmost practical strictly economic\nmeans for checking the recession.\nThere is, accordingly, very earnest\nconjecture as to the meaning and\nprobable consequences of the reduc\ntion of $4 a ton on cold-rolled sheet\nsteel\u2014-a material used extensively by\nautomobile manufacturers.\nAlternatives in the outlook are sum\nmarized by the Annalist when it says:\n\u2019'Whether this reduction is a major\nstep toward the resolution of the\nprevailing uncertainty over the price\noiitlodk, which in turn is believed to\nbe a major Influence depressing busi\nness, or whether it is merely the\nbeginning of what may be a rather\nlong-drawn-out period of readjust\nment, remains to be seen.\u201d If- one\ndares to admit a positive note o.f\nprophecy there Is nothing better\nreasoned In sight than what the New\nYork Times calls stock market con-\njecture. \u201cCurrent guessing,\u201d the\nTimes said in its financial columns\non Friday, \u2019'seems to tend toward\nthe belief that lower steel prices and\nlower steel wages may come to pass\neventually and that it is unlikely that\nthere will be one without the other.\"\nThe actual reductions put into ef\nfect in steel prices are limited in\nextent. -They can be regarded mere\nly as an internal adjustment. The\nmagazine Steel says today: \"Reduc\ntion of $2 per ton in the base price\nof cold-rolled sheets and abolition of\nthe former extra of $2 a ton for oil\ning brings that grade of sheets to a\nparity with its competitive material,\nhot-rolled, single-pickled and oiled\nsheets.\" But any substantial conces\nsion in an important sector .of the\nsteel market will cause buyers to\nlook for other concessions.\nThe national administration desires\nlower steel prices, both because it is\na heavy prospective buyer of steel\nand because it-. believes that lower\nprices will stimulate building con\nstruction and ether capital goods in\ndustries. The 'administration's at\ntitude has been complicated by the\nPresident's statement regarding wages\n\u2014a subject over which he has no di\nrect authority, hut in regard to\nwhich, through government boards\nand political contacts, the adminis\ntration is able to wield considerable\nauthority. It is unlikely, however,\nthat there will be any general or\nsubstantial reduction in steel prices\nwithout a lowering of wage costs.\nThe government\u2019s spokesmen have\nnot said that all steel prices could\nba reduced without reducing wages.\nThey have merely said that some\nsteel prices could be so'reduced.\nMay Be Beneficial\nIf, therefore, -the past week's de-\nvelopments can be regarded as a step\ntoward'an all-round reduction in steel\nprices, with a prospect of such wage\nadjustments as are necessary to make\nthe reductions feasible, there is a\n.considerably improved prospect of\nchecking the recession, though the\nimmediate unsettlement may be great\ner. Something further is needed to\n\u2019restore confidence, to be sure, per\nhaps along the line of suggestions\nmade by the oig and little business\nmen in the Washington conferences.\nBut there is ut least a belief that\n\u2019Congress is genuinely concerned\nabout the present recession and is\neager to quicken the pace of busi\nness.\nThe Indexes of business activity\nthat were advancing slightly have\nreturned downward again, but there\nis still reason to hope that the sharp\ndecline of August to December will\nnot be resumed. Commodity prices\nhave also slumped further, but a\nmoderate upturn in buying in two\nor three major branches would have\na fairly wide steadying effect. The\nstock market, which both advanced\nand declined during the week, suf\nfered more from dullness than it did\nfrom weakness.\nThe dollar was again weak in rela\ntion to foreign currencies; the slump\non Friday was at first attributed to\nthe President's request for $250,000,000\nfor relief purposes, which was said\nto have been interpreted abroad as\na sign that the United States was\nstarting on a program of heavy\nspending, which would carry it in\nthe direction of inflation. The New\nYork Times said on Saturday, how\never: \"There appeared to be no\n-grounds for belief that weakness in\nthe dollar was linked to President\nRoosevelt\u2019s request for an additional\nrelief appropriation of $250,000,000.\"\nReports of a weakening in Nazi rule\nsoem to have strengthened foreign\ncurrencies, and this, rather than any\nfresh fears about the dollar, was\nheld responsible for the advance in\nquotations.\nOutlook for Railroads\nT|ie ending of the Interstate Com\nmerce'commission's hearings on the\nrailroads' rate petition fostered a more\noptimistic feeling with regard to rail\nroads. The rate advances'to be au\nthorized are likely to be announced\nIn a few weeks, and should prove\nsufficient to offset some recent in\ncreases in operating costs, particular\nly the wage advances, higher costs\nof eoal and soci il security taxes. There\nwill probably be Borne disappointment\nwhen they are announced, but, on\nsecond thoughts, failure to secure the\nrequested revenue will be considered\nfar from deplorable.\nThe railroads are compelled to ask\nfor higher rates, but. they are doing\n.so at an unfortunate time, when an\nincrease' in transportation charges\nwill not be beneficial to husinAs.\nThere are differences of opinion as\nto the possibilities of the loss of\nfurther business to trucks. Some\nthink that this has now gone about\nSa far as is probable, but higher\nrates will mean some further diver\nsion of traffic. Probably the best\noutcome for the railroads will be the\ngranting of sufficient revenue to meet\nthe Immediate demands of solvency, to\nbe followed by a prompt study of\nmethods for reducing the railroads'\ncoats of operation.\nNorfolk. Va.. Feb. 13-( API\ntanker Pennsylvania Sun. damaged by\ntwo collisions at sea within 24 hours,\nheaded for Marcus Hook tonight for\nrepairs.\nThe Coast guard reported that the\ntanker, which was In collision with\nthe Hondurnn motorship Castilla late\nSaturday, collided with the Norwegian\nfreighter Gunny at 3.30 a. m. (E.8.T.)\ntoday.\nSOCIAL SECURITY\nTAX STAMPS URGED\nTO AID COLLECTING\nCommentator Approves Sim\nplification of System Pro\nposed at Conference of Lit\ntle Businessmen\nNew York, Feb. 11 \u2014Little business\nmen last week suggested the use of\nstamps as the means of collecting\nsocial security taxes.\nThis seems like such an obviously\nsensible proposal that many will\nwonder why it was not adopted in\nthe first place instead of the elaborate\nbookkeeping and report making cur\nrently required.\nApparently the answers is that the\nactive proponents of social insurance\nin the United States remembered that\nwhen Lloyd George first introduced\nthe refer min the United Kingdom,\nthe protest centered around the con\ncrete act of stamp licking.\nWith stamp licking obviated over\nhere, the public has been extra\nordinarily complacent, even though\nthe old age benefit taxes started on\nJanuary 1, 1937 whereas the, regular\nbenefit payments do not begin until\n1942.\nHowever, now that the Idea of\nsocial security has won popular ac\nceptance, there ought to be no ob\njection to switching over to the stamp\nsystem, which would enormously re\nduce the cost of compliance by work\ners and employers and at the same\ntime curtail the number of super\nvisory operations by both the treasury\nand the social security board.\nBut there is a vastly more signifi\ncant departure from the British pre\ncedent, which was left unnoticed in\nthe Washington parley.\nBritish Pension Plan\nThe British contributory old age\npension play provided that the initial\nbenefits to persons W\u2019ho become elig\nible in the early years of the plan\nshould be. precisely the same as those\npayable ultimately to those w\u2019ho\nreached the retirement age a few de\ncades thereafter.\nThe social security act did precisely\nthe opposite. It not only leaves out\nthose who become sixty-five prior to\n1924, but also thereafter provides\naverage pensions in 1942 of but sl7\na month compared with average pen\nsions forty years later of 850 a month.\nBy 1950, average pensions will reach\n821 a month; by 1960, S2B a month;\nand by 1970, 835 a month. These are\nnot maximum pensions, but the com\nputed averages.\nAccordingly when men now in the\ni late forties, fifties, or early sixties\nreach retirement age. they are due for\na great shock. They will find that\nthe hope. of substantia! benefits lies\nonly in the far distant future\u2014and is\nnot for them.\nBut there is a worse aspect to the\nsituation. In another section of the\nsame act there is provision for fed\neral aid to state old age assistance\nschemes, based on a means test. Such\nnoncontributory payments, or doles,\nwill be vastly larger than the pensions\nreceived by retired workers, who with\ni their employers, contributed to the\nfund.\nAs a matter of fact, such non\ncontributory old age doles euri'ently\naverage more than sl9 a month, com\npared with the sl7 average for con\ntributory old age benefits payable in\n1942. In seven states, such old age\nassistance now exceeds $25 a month.\nAnd in some states both the husband\nand wife are entitled to the pay\nment.\nUnder Old-Age Doles\nNow under the existing setup, old\nage benefit payments for 20 years are\nlikely to be substantially under old\nage assistance doles. Those who have\nbeen trying to pay toward their own\npensions may thus be forced to seek\nto supplement it with a dole.\nMeantime, during these early years\nof inadequate benefits, pay roll taxes\nwill vastly exceed the amounts paid\nout. Thus the persons retiring In the\nfirst two decades will be crucified by\nthe foolish effort to accumulate a\nhuge acturial reserve. The remedy lies\nin adopting something comparable to\nthe full benefit schedules at the out\nset, and dispensing with the large re\nserve. which is unnecessary. The\nscheme can he financed more nearly\non a pay-as-you-go basis, with a\nmoderate contingency reserve.\nReferring to this problem, the non\npartisan social security commission\nsponsored by the Hearst, newspapers,\non which this writer acted as chair\nman, recommended: \"Accumulation of\na large reserve could be obviated\neither by postponing the tax increases\nscheduled to begin in 1940 or by\naugmenting the benefit payments to\nthose now of advanced age so that\neach year most of the income from\nthe current pay-roll taxes would he\ndisbursed as benefits to retired work\ners who have reached the age of 65.\n\"The commission favors a combina\ntion of these two methods.\"\nWEEKLY REVIEW\nOF BOND MARKET\nRail Loans Provide Another\nBroad Rally Recovery\nMovement Credited to\nShift in Psychology\nNew York. Feb. 18 \u2014(AP) \u2014Active\ntrading Interest In last week's bond\nmarket ngnln converged on rail loans,\nwhich provided another broad rally.\nMoving ahead at a better tempo than\nin the previous week, many leading\ncarriers piled up new gains which\nstretched cumulative recoveries from\nJanuary lows to 5 to 12 points.\nThe Associated Press rail average\nof 20 rails at Friday's close indi\ncated recovery of almost half of the\nhuge January losses, most of which\ncame Io the wake of Erie railroad's\nmove for reorganization.\nAt 65.1 the composite was up a\nfull 5 points from the. five-year low\nmark set January 28.\nTrading circles associated the ex\ntended recovery with a change In In\nveatment psychology. Fears over the\nfuture of some carriers had been\neased. It was pointed out. by opti\nmistic comment by certain important\nrail executives, and a general rise of\nconfidence, in investment quarters In\nthe outcome of the carriers' case for\nhigher freight rates.\nUtility and industrial liens provided\nsome wide swings both ways chiefly\nin the inactive categories. The aver\nages made small gains on the week.\nThe cloudy business outlook, and\nforecasts ot sharply lower Industrial\nprofits in the first quarter put s ime\nrestraint on trading activities in the\nIndustrial division.\nTHE SPRINGFIELD WEEKLY REPUBLICAN; SPRINGFIELD, MASS.: THURSDAY, FEBRUARY 17, 193?\nRoosevelt May Try to Block\nSlump in Commodity Prices\nWashington, Feb. 15 \u2014(AP) The\nadministration may take steps to stop\nthe decline of commodity prices,\nPresident Roosevelt indicated today.\nHe told reporters that the prices\nare too low. and should go up\u2014but\nnot too much.\nA report on the price situation by\na group of federal statisticians, who\nbegan conferences today at the treas\nury. is expected to be in Mr Roose\nvelt\u2019s desk by Thursday.\nLatest figures of the labor statistics\nbureau show that wholesale com\nmodity prices are only about 80 per\ncent of the 1926 level, which Roosevelt\nFARMERS HOLDING\nSTOCK OFF MARKET,\nDEALERS ASSERT\nMild Moratorium Suspected\nby Livestock Men, Who\nSee Independent Effort to\nBolster Prices\nChicago, Feb. 9 \u2014(AP) \u2014Alert live\nstock dealers, scanning dwindling\nmeat animal supplies at the nation\u2019s\nmajor stockyards, today detected evi\ndence of what they called a mild\nfarmers' marketing moratorium.\nBad roads, storms, floods and bliz\nzards have played an important part\nin reducing the market ward flow of\nlivestock and a seasonal contraction\nin receipts is normal at this time of\nyear, but a sharp falling off of sup\nplies the past few days attracted par\nticular attention in the trade. Not\nonce this week have Chicago arrivals\nequaled advance estimates based\nlargely on reports of farmers' loading\nintentions.\nDealers said producers and feeders,\nacting independently although in har\nmony, have been cutting shipments\nto market partly in an effort to bol\nster prices.\nHog receipts at the nation\u2019s 20\nprincipal markets so far this week\nwere 17 per cent less than in the\ncorresponding period last week. Cattle\nreceipts have been cut 18 per cent.\nHog supplies last week were 17 per\ncent less than the previous week\nwhile the cattle run was 12 per cent\nless.\nGENERAL ELECTRIC\nHAS \u2018NO INTENTION\u2019\nOF CUTTING WAGES\n\u2018Perfect Harmony\u2019 Reported\nin Contract Conferences\nWith Union \u2014Pittsfield Ex\npected to Benefit\nNew York. Feb. 10\u2014(AP)\u2014Pro\nfessing \"perfect harmony\u201d in their\nnegotiations for a working contract.\nGeneral Electric company officials and\nC. I. O. union representatives recessed\ntonight with the reassurance from a\ncompany official that \"we have^ no\nintention now of lowering wages.\u201d\nAt\". R. Burrows, General Electric\nvice-president, voiced that promise\nand added: \u201cI hope we shall not\nhave to consider it at any time.\"\nJulius Emspak. general secretary\nof the United Electrical and Radio\nWorkers, agreed with Burrows that\nwages and hours were not at issue\nin the negotltions, which will be re\nsumed tomorrow.\nConcerns 35,000 Workers\nSome 35,000 workers in General\nElectric plants in eight cities would\nbe governed by the contract, and\nEmspak said that ultimately it was\nhoped a total of 55.000 General Elec\ntric employes would be covered.\n\u201cThe present discussions.\" Burrow\nsaid, \"are concerned mainly with\nputting iuto writing conditions that\nnow obtain in our plants.\"\nUnion officials, who said they hoped\nagreement would be reached within\na week, reported that a 40-hour-week\nand time-and-a-half for overtime now\nprevail in the plants but that a wide\npay differential for various work\ncategories exists.\nThe agreement would apply to\nworkers in General Electric plants\nat Schenectady, N. Y.; Lynn. Mass.:\nBloomfield. N. J.: Philadelphia and\nNew Kensington. Pa.: Cleveland, O.:\nFort Wayne, Ind.; and Bridgeport,\nCt.\nMay Reach Pittsfield\nIt was reliably learned that the\nmatter of bringing newly organized\nlocals under the contract on their\nattaining a majority membership is\nbeing discussed in present confer\nences. Among the locals which the\nunion expects soon to incorporate\nin its contractual benefits are those\nof York, Pa., and Pittsfield. Mass.\nIndicative of the \"perfect harmony\"\nof the conferences was an exchange\nof compliments by the company and\nunion representatives.\n\u201cThose union fellows are perfect\nly grand,\" said Burrows. \"We are\nhaving no difficulties whatsoever.\"\nInformed ot Burrows's compliment.\nEmspak told a reporter, \u201cYou can\nsay we think he's a nice man.\"\nEmspak and Burrows both agreed\nthere was no barrier or complication\nnow foreseen to conclusion of an\nagreement. Burrows, in charge ot\nmanufacturing, alone represented the\nGeneral Electric company in today's\nconference. Eleven union delegates\nfrom several cities eat tn.\nASKS BANK EXECUTIVES\nBE CIVEN MORE TIME\nCurrency Controller Cites\nSincere Effort to Repay\nPre-1933 Debts to Banks\nWashington. Feb. 9\u2014(API\u2014J. F. T.\nO'Connor, retiring controller of the\ncurrency, urged Congress today to\ngive bank executives another year to\nrepay pre-1933 debts to their instl\ntutions. The banking act of 1933 pro\nhibited loans by banks belonging to\nthe Federal Reserve system to their\nofficers, but gave them two years to\nliquidate existing indebtedness. This\ndeadline was extended In 3935 until\nJune 15. 1938.\nO\u2019Connor said in his annual report\ntoday that the bankers had made a\nsincere effort to pay up and since\n1933 have reduced direct obligations\n69.83 per cent an^ indirect obligations\nby 82.11 per cent. On June 30, 1937.\nthey still owed 893.743,000 directly and\n$43,487,000 indirectly.\nhas described as a normal level. A\nyear ago the index was 85.4\nThe immediate concern of federal\neconomists recently has been the con\ntinued tendency of prices to fall al\nthough the decline In industrial pro\nduction seems to have stopped, at\nleast temporarily, and retail trade has\nnot suffered, comparatively speaking.\nSome officials indicated that yes\nterday's action of the treasury In\npartially abandoning its gold steriliza\ntion program was intended to bolster\ncommodity prices. They said that, at\nleast psychologically, the action was\ninflationary and might strengthen\nprices.\nAYRES SAYS RAILS\nIN SUCH JAM U. S.\nMAY HAVE TO HELP\nBusiness Statistician Fears\n\u2018Fundamental Change If\nReal Depression Prevails\nThroughout Year\u2019\nCleveland, Feb. 10 \u2014(AP) \u2014Col Leon\nard P. Ayres told the Traffic club of\nCleveland tonight that 1938 may\nbring a fundamental change in Amer\nican transportation \"if real depression\nconditions prevail\u201d throughout the\nyea r.\n\"It may well be,\" he said, \"that 1938\nwill prove to be the year in which\nthe affairs of the railroads will be\ncome so complicated that the federal\ngovernment, which has regulated them\nfor the past 50 years, will finally\nundertake to find solutions for their\nproblem.\u201d\nCol Ayres, a well-known business\nstatistician and a member of the ex\necutive committee of Alleghany cor\nporation, railroad holding company,\nspoke on \u201cThe outlook for traffic in\n1938.\u201d\nHe pointed out that the operating\nratio of fall class 1 roads advanced to\n81 at the end of last year\u2014in other\nwords 81 per cent of operating rev\nenues went to cover operating ex\npenses, leaving approximately one\nfifth for fixed charges.\nSees Billion Fixed Charges Left\nFixed charges, including interest\npayments, taxes and \u201cother unescap\nable deductions such as equipment\nrents,\u201d Col Ayres said, \u201cwill be so\nlarge in 1938 that after roads have\nused all their nonoperating income\nin defraying them, they will still have\none billion dollars of fixed charges\nleft which must be paid out of oper\nating revenues.\u201d\n\u201cIf that enormous sum Is to be\npaid out of one-fifth of the operating\nrevenues,\u201d Col Ayres declared, \"then\nthose revenues will have to amount to\nfive billions, which is far more than\nthey have been in any year since 1930\nand far more than there is any pros\npect of them being in 1938.\u201d\nIt increased freight rates now be\ning considered in Washington were\ngranted, the operating ratio might\ndrop as low as 75, he said, and \u201cin\nthat case in order to meet fixed\ncharges of one billion dollars the roads\nwould have to have operating revenues\nof four times that much, or four\nbillion dollars.\u201d\n\"At present there is little prospect\nthat they will have either operating\nrevenues as high as four billion dol\nlars, or an operating ratio as low as\n75,\" he added.\nUtilities Key In Slump Jam\nHe repeated his assertion in previ\nous addresses that \u201cthe electric utili\nties are the keylog in our depression\njam\" and said \"if there could be a\ntreaty of peace between the utilities\nand the government, more than a\nbillion dollars' worth a year of new\nconstruction could promptly be got\nunder way.\u201d\nCol Ayres said \"there are disturb\ning Indications that business depres\nsion Is beginning in Europe\" and\nadded that \"if that continues to de\nvelop our chances for a prompt and\nvigorous recovery here are not good.\u201d\nN. E. POWER HOPES\nRECESSION ENDING\nFact 15 Per Cent Drop in\nOutput Is About Same in\nRecent Weeks Seen Sign\nBottom Has Been Hit\nBoston, Feb. 9\u2014(AP)\u2014The New\nEngland Power association tonight an\nnounced a 15 per cent decrease in the\nkilowatt-hour primary production of\nthe operating companies in its sys\ntem as compared to a year ago.\nAsserting that the \"rate of decrease\nhas been about the same in recent\nweeks,\" Frank D. Comerford, chair\nman of the association, said. \"This\nindicates the hope that business has\nhit the bottom, but as yet there is\nno definite basis for an expectation of\nimprovement.\"\nComerford said the decline \"began\nin the latter part of the summer of\n1937 as a result of the business re\ncession.\" He added that since De\ncember. 1937, the decrease, compared\nwith the same periods last year,\nranged between 15 to 20 per cent.\nJones Promises\nAdequate Loans\nWashington. Feb. 10\u2014(AP)\u2014Chair\nman Jesse H. Jones ot the Recon\nstruction Finance Corporation ruled\nout tonight, as unnecessary and im\npractical. atl suggestions for govern\nment financial aid to email business\nmen, except the present RFC system.\nHe indicated he might urge Presi\ndent Roosevelt to lift certain rest\nraints placed on RFC lending last\nOctober, but dismissed other propo\nsals with the comment. \"I think wr\nhave all the (legislative) authority\nneeded.\"\nHe asserted emphatically that he\nwould not risk the government's\nmoney in inadequately secured loans\nnor gamble on the purchase of stock\nin any private business.\nBANK OF U. S. URGED\nBY WILLIAM LEMKE\nHartford. Ct.. Feb. 18\u2014(AP)\u2014Con\ngiesaman William bemke ot North\nDakota tonight urged the establish\nment of a hank of the United States\nto be \"run by the people\" and blamed\nPresident Roosevelt for the continu\nance ot the recession.\nHe told nearly 1000 persons, many\not them members of the National\nUnion for Social Justice, that \"we\nhave everything at our fingertips to\nmake thia the greatest country tn the\nworld except intelligence in Wash\nington.\"\nNEW YORK STOCK MARKET\nSale of Stocks\nSaw York Stock exchange SMJH6\nNew York Carh exchange 1*6^)000\nBoston Stock exchange 1438*\nSTOCK AVERAGES\n(.Compiled by the Associated Preet)\nM 1* 15 60\nInd. Rails BtlhStk?.\nNet change \u2014.4 \u2014.2 \u2014-4\nPrevlona day 63.8 19.5 80.9 44.2\nMonth ago 66.6 20.5 83.6 46.6\nYear ago 99.7 41.8 51.8 7\u00bbJ\n1988 high 68,2 21.6 *4.9 47.9\n1988 low 59.2 17.6 *O.O 413\n1937 high 161.6 49.5 54.0 75.8\n1987 low 57.7 19.0 *1.6 41.7\nMovement In Recent Yean\n1932 low 17.5 8.7 28.9 16.9\n1929 high 146.9 153.9 184.3 157.7\n1927 low 51.6 95.8 6LB 613\nNew York, 'Feb. 15\u2014(AP)\u2014The\nstock market encountered selling flur\nries today after an early rally and\nleading issues dipped fractions to as\nmuch as 2 points.\nA crack in Chicago grain prices\nhelped to reverse the upward trend,\nobservers declared. Other factors\nthey said, were profit selling and the\nstatement of Secretary Morgenthau\nbefore a congressional committee that\nthe business situation \"is most acute.\u201d\nHe added, however, the recession was\nleveling out. but declined to predict\nwhen a bottom might be reached.\nVirtual suspension by the treasury\nof its gold sterilization program was\nregarded In Wall street as mildly In\nflationary in its psychological aspects,\nbut had little effect on the market\nexcept to boost gold mining stocks in\nthe final hour.\nVolume failed to pick up much and\ntransfers totaled only 523.319 shares\ncompared with 400.870 yesterday. The\nAssociated Press average of 60 stocks\nslipped .4 of a point at 43.8.\nThe sage of 2% to cents a\nbushel in wheat carried with it the\ncoarse grains. Corn lost to\ncents. Cotton finished 20 cents a bale\nlower to 25 cents higher. Other com\nmodities were mixed.\nBonds fared better than stocks, and\nwhile advances were mostly in frac\ntions gains were general throughout\nthe list. With gold at London at\na new 1938 high. European cour\nrencies climbed against the dollar in\nforeign exchange transactions. Bank\ners said a mild movement of funds\nfrom this country was in progress.\nSteels, which had led the morning\u2019s\nrecovery efforts in the stock market,\nwere pounded in the afternoon sell\ning and some fairly sizable losses re\nsulted. Others tn suffer were the\ncoppers, farm implements and motors.\nActive on the downturn, with losses\nrunning a point nr mnre. were United\nStates Steel. 52%. Bethlehem 54%,\nChrvsler 54%. Kennecott 35%. Ana\nconda 30%. International Harvester\n63. Deere 21. du Pont 114%. Westing\nhouse 94%. American Telephone\n135%. Santa Fe 35%. United States\nRubber 28%, and Union Carbide 73%.\nHomestake Mining 62%. and 